More generally, if there are formula_23 possible realizations of formula_15, namely formula_16 but with possibly unequal probabilities formula_26 for formula_17, then the covariance is
formula_28

In the case where two discrete random variables formula_1 and formula_2 have a joint probability distribution, represented by elements formula_31 corresponding to the joint probabilities of formula_32, the covariance is calculated using a double summation over the indices of the matrix:

