===Uncorrelatedness and independence===

Random variables whose covariance is zero are called uncorrelated. Similarly, the components of random vectors whose covariance matrix is zero in every entry outside the main diagonal are also called uncorrelated.

If formula_1 and formula_2 are independent random variables, then their covariance is zero. This follows because under independence,
formula_67

The converse, however, is not generally true. For example, let formula_1 be uniformly distributed in formula_69 and let formula_70. Clearly, formula_1 and formula_2 are not independent, but
formula_73

In this case, the relationship between formula_2 and formula_1 is non-linear, while correlation and covariance are measures of linear dependence between two random variables. This example shows that if two random variables are uncorrelated, that does not in general imply that they are independent. However, if two variables are jointly normally distributed (but not if they are merely individually normally distributed), uncorrelatedness &quot;does&quot; imply independence.

formula_1 and formula_2 whose covariance is positive are called positively correlated, which implies if formula_78 then likely formula_79. Conversely, formula_1 and formula_2 with negative covariance are negatively correlated, and if formula_78 then likely formula_83.

=== Relationship to inner products ===
Many of the properties of covariance can be extracted elegantly by observing that it satisfies similar properties to those of an inner product:
# bilinear: for constants formula_84 and formula_85 and random variables formula_86 formula_87
# symmetric: formula_88
# positive semi-definite: formula_89 for all random variables formula_1, and formula_91 implies that formula_1 is constant almost surely.

In fact these properties imply that the covariance defines an inner product over the quotient vector space obtained by taking the subspace of random variables with finite second moment and identifying any two that differ by a constant. (This identification turns the positive semi-definiteness above into positive definiteness.) That quotient vector space is isomorphic to the subspace of random variables with finite second moment and mean zero; on that subspace, the covariance is exactly the L2 inner product of real-valued functions on the sample space.

As a result, for random variables with finite variance, the inequality
formula_93
holds via the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.

Proof: If formula_94, then it holds trivially. Otherwise, let random variable
